  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        True/False. For each of the following, write T if the statement is
        true; otherwise, write F. You do NOT need to provide explanations or show work for this problem. Throughout, let <m>G</m> be a group with identity element <m>e</m>.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>G</m> is infinite and cyclic, then <m>G</m> must have infinitely many generators.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              There may be two distinct elements <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> of a group <m>G</m> with <m>\langle a\rangle =\langle b\rangle</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>a,b\in G</m> and <m>a\in \langle b\rangle</m> then we must have <m>b\in \langle a\rangle</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>a\in G</m> with <m>a^4=e</m>, then <m>o(a)</m> must equal <m>4</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>G</m> is countable then <m>G</m> must be cyclic.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
    <ol cols="5">
      <li>
        <p>
          F
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          T
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          F
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          F
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          F
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol></p>
  </solution>
   </exercise>
 
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Give examples of the following.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              An infinite noncyclic group <m>G</m> containing an infinite cyclic subgroup <m>H</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              An infinite noncyclic group <m>G</m> containing a finite nontrivial cyclic subgroup <m>H</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              A cyclic group <m>G</m> containing exactly 20 elements.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              A nontrivial cyclic group <m>G</m> whose elements are all matrices.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              A noncyclic group <m>G</m> such that every proper subgroup of <m>G</m> is cyclic.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
 
  <solution>
    
    <p>
      (Other answers are possible.)
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>G=\R</m>, <m>H=\Z</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>G=GL(n,\R)</m>, <m>H=\{\pm I_2\}</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>G=\Z_{20}</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>G=\{\pm I_2\}</m>, under matrix multiplication
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>G=\Z_2^2</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </solution>
   </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find the orders of the following elements in the given groups.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>2\in \Z</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>-i\in \C^*</m>
 
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>-I_2\in GL(2,\R)</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>-I_2\in \M_2(\R)</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>(6,8)\in \Z_{10}\times \Z_{10}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  
  <solution>
    <p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>o(2)=\infty</m>, since <m>\langle 2\rangle =2\Z</m>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          <m>o(-i)=4</m>, since <m>\langle -i\rangle =\{-i,-1,i,1\}</m>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          <m>o(I_2)=2</m>, since <m>\langle -I_2\rangle =\{-I_2,I_2\}</m>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          <m>o(I_2)=\infty</m>, since <m>\langle -I_2\rangle =\{kI_2\,:\,k\in \Z\}</m>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          <m>o((6,8))=5</m>, since <m>\langle (6,8)\rangle =\{(6,8),(2,6),(8,4),(4,2),(0,0)\}</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol></p>
  </solution>
  </exercise>

