   <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>G</m> be a group with no nontrivial proper subgroups. Prove that <m>G</m> is cyclic.
      </p>
    </statement>

  <solution>
    
    <p>
      Let <m>e</m> be the identity
      element of <m>G</m>. If <m>G=\{e\}</m>, then <m>G</m> is clearly
      cyclic. Else, there exists <m>a\neq e</m> in <m>G</m>. Then
      <m>\langle a\rangle</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m>. Since <m>e\neq a\in
      \langle a\rangle</m>, <m>\langle a\rangle</m> is a nontrivial subgroup of <m>G</m>. Therefore, we must have
      <m>\langle a\rangle =G</m>. Hence, <m>G</m> is cyclic, as desired.
    </p>
  </solution>
  </exercise>
